ce:section.ce:para:
The electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) carried out in 0.4 mM DA also confirmed the superiority of GCE/CQDs/CuO for DA detection compared to other electrodes. Fig. 6 A depicts the Nyquist plot of EIS spectra for the bare and the modified electrodes in DA. The Randles equivalent circuit X (Fig. 7
                     B) represents the equivalent circuit for the EIS spectrum of GCE/CQDs/CuO. On the other hand, the equivalent circuit Y (Fig. 7B) represents the circuit used for fitting the EIS spectra of bare GCE, GCE/CQDs and GCE/CuO. The charge transfer resistance (Rct) obtained from the EIS spectra of bare GCE, GCE/CuO, GCE/CQDs, and GCE/CQDs/CuO were 12.5, 32.4, 91.2, and 9.8 kΩ, respectively (Table 1
                     ). There was a drastic drop in Rct obtained with GCE/CQDs after the addition of CuO (as seen in Rct of GCE/CQDs/CuO), revealing the conductivity of the CuO nanoparticles (Fig. 6). This suggests that introducing CuO nanoparticles into CQDs gives a composite that allows better electron transfer than the CuO nanoparticles, thereby improving DA electrocatalytic oxidation at the GCE/CQDs/CuO. The very low Rct obtained with GCE/CQDs/CuO is also a clear indication that the combination of the CQDs and CuO NPs is highly beneficial for detecting DA at the nanocomposite modified electrode. Similar improvement in the rate of electron flow through a composite made from rGO and α-Fe2O3 for DA detection compared to individual materials has been reported [26]. Matthew et al.[26] confirmed that the synergy between the individual materials was responsible for the composite’s better electronic conductivity than that of the individual materials (rGO and α-Fe2O3). The bare GCE has lower Rct than GCE/CQDs and GCE/CuO, suggesting that the CQDs and CuO offered higher resistance to electron transfer than the bare GCE. Contrastingly, GCE/CuO gave higher DA oxidation current than bare GCE. This Rct trend (Table 1) suggests that the conductivity of the CuO NPs might not be the only reason for the higher CV oxidation current response obtained with GCE/CuO compared to bare GCE (Fig. 6). The large surface area of the CuO NPs could have played a more significant role in obtaining a better current response than the bare GCE. Table 1 shows the EIS parameters such as the solution resistance (Rs), Warburg impedance (W), Rct, the constant phase element (CPE) and its exponent (n) obtained from the EIS data fitting. The error associated with each circuit element has been placed in parenthesis.
